---
import PageLayout from '../../layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import FIRECalculatorBase from '../../components/calculator/FIRECalculatorBase.astro';
---

<PageLayout
  title="Fat FIRE Calculator — Plan Your Luxury Early Retirement"
  description="Free Fat FIRE calculator for high earners who want to maintain their lifestyle in early retirement. Calculate your FIRE number using the 30x multiplier. Interactive charts and instant results."
  canonical="https://truefinancetools.com/fat-fire-calculator"
  ogImage="https://truefinancetools.com/og-fat-fire-calculator.png"
  ogImageAlt="Fat FIRE Calculator - Plan Your Luxury Early Retirement"
  pageType="article"
  keywords="fat fire calculator, fat fire number, luxury retirement, high income retirement, fire calculator 30x, fat fire strategy"
>
    <FIRECalculatorBase fireType="fat" />

    <section class="border-t border-hairline bg-canvas-soft py-16">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 sm:px-6">
        <h2 class="mb-8 text-center text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-ink" style="letter-spacing: -0.02em;">
          What is Fat FIRE?
        </h2>

        <div class="prose prose-gray max-w-none text-body">
          <p class="mb-4">
            <strong>Fat FIRE</strong> is for high earners who want to maintain their current lifestyle in retirement. It requires <strong>30x your annual expenses</strong> saved — the most conservative multiplier among all FIRE strategies.
          </p>

          <p class="mb-4">
            Unlike Lean FIRE or Regular FIRE, Fat FIRE doesn't require lifestyle sacrifices. If you earn $200,000+ per year and want to keep spending at that level in retirement, Fat FIRE gives you the financial cushion to do so.
          </p>

          <h3 class="mb-3 text-lg font-semibold text-ink">The Fat FIRE Formula</h3>
          <div class="rounded-lg bg-canvas-soft-2 p-4 font-mono text-sm text-ink">
            Fat FIRE Number = Annual Expenses × 30
          </div>

          <p class="mb-4">
            For example, if you spend $80,000 per year, your Fat FIRE number is $2,400,000. That's $400,000 more than Regular FIRE ($2,000,000) for the same expenses — but it provides a larger safety margin.
          </p>

          <h3 class="mb-3 text-lg font-semibold text-ink">Who Should Choose Fat FIRE?</h3>
          <div class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
            <div class="rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4">
              <h4 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink">High Earners</h4>
              <p class="text-sm text-body">Professionals earning $150K+ who want to maintain their lifestyle without compromise.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4">
              <h4 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink">Families</h4>
              <p class="text-sm text-body">Parents who need to cover children's education, healthcare, and family travel.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4">
              <h4 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink">Healthcare Focus</h4>
              <p class="text-sm text-body">Those who want premium healthcare coverage and don't want to rely on ACA subsidies.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4">
              <h4 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink">Travel Enthusiasts</h4>
              <p class="text-sm text-body">People who plan to travel extensively and need a larger budget for experiences.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="border-t border-hairline bg-canvas-soft py-16">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 sm:px-6">
        <h2 class="mb-8 text-center text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-ink" style="letter-spacing: -0.02em;">
          Lean FIRE vs Fat FIRE: Which Strategy Is Right for You?
        </h2>

        <div class="prose prose-gray max-w-none text-body">
          <p class="mb-4">
            The debate between <strong>Lean FIRE vs Fat FIRE</strong> comes down to one question: how much lifestyle flexibility do you want in retirement? Lean FIRE requires just <strong>20x your annual expenses</strong> while Fat FIRE requires <strong>30x</strong> — a difference that can mean years of extra saving versus years of extra freedom. Understanding this gap is the first step to choosing the right FIRE strategy for your goals.
          </p>

          <h3 class="mb-3 text-lg font-semibold text-ink">Lean FIRE vs Fat FIRE: The Numbers</h3>

          <div class="overflow-x-auto">
            <table class="mb-6 w-full text-sm">
              <thead>
                <tr class="border-b border-hairline">
                  <th class="pb-3 pr-4 text-left font-semibold text-ink">Factor</th>
                  <th class="pb-3 pr-4 text-left font-semibold text-ink">Lean FIRE</th>
                  <th class="pb-3 text-left font-semibold text-ink">Fat FIRE</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody class="text-body">
                <tr class="border-b border-hairline">
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-medium text-ink">Multiplier</td>
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4">20x annual expenses</td>
                  <td class="py-3">30x annual expenses</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-hairline">
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-medium text-ink">Target on $50K spending</td>
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4">$1,000,000</td>
                  <td class="py-3">$1,500,000</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-hairline">
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-medium text-ink">Target on $80K spending</td>
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4">$1,600,000</td>
                  <td class="py-3">$2,400,000</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-hairline">
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-medium text-ink">Target on $120K spending</td>
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4">$2,400,000</td>
                  <td class="py-3">$3,600,000</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-hairline">
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-medium text-ink">Withdrawal rate</td>
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4">5%</td>
                  <td class="py-3">3.33%</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-hairline">
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-medium text-ink">Lifestyle</td>
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4">Minimalist, frugal</td>
                  <td class="py-3">Comfortable, luxury</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-medium text-ink">Time to reach</td>
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4">Faster (5-10 years less)</td>
                  <td class="py-3">Slower (more saving needed)</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <h3 class="mb-3 text-lg font-semibold text-ink">Key Differences Between Lean FIRE and Fat FIRE</h3>

          <p class="mb-4">
            <strong>Budget flexibility:</strong> Lean FIRE retirees typically live on $25,000–$50,000 per year, relying on lower fixed costs and the ability to cut discretionary spending during market downturns. Fat FIRE retirees spend $80,000–$200,000+ per year, maintaining their pre-retirement lifestyle without compromise.
          </p>

          <p class="mb-4">
            <strong>Safety margin:</strong> Fat FIRE's 30x multiplier provides a larger cushion against unexpected expenses — medical emergencies, market crashes, or inflation spikes. Lean FIRE's 20x multiplier is still sustainable over 30+ years, but requires more flexibility to adjust spending when needed.
          </p>

          <p class="mb-4">
            <strong>Time trade-off:</strong> On a $50,000 annual budget, the $500,000 gap between Lean FIRE ($1,000,000) and Fat FIRE ($1,500,000) could represent 5–10 additional years of work. That is the core trade-off: retire sooner with less, or work longer for more comfort.
          </p>

          <h3 class="mb-3 text-lg font-semibold text-ink">Lean FIRE vs Fat FIRE: Who Should Choose Which?</h3>

          <p class="mb-4">
            Choose <strong>Lean FIRE</strong> if you are a minimalist, digital nomad, or live in a low cost-of-living area. It is ideal for people who value time freedom over material comfort and are willing to maintain a leaner budget in exchange for retiring years earlier.
          </p>

          <p class="mb-4">
            Choose <strong>Fat FIRE</strong> if you are a high earner ($150K+) who wants to maintain your current lifestyle, travel frequently, cover premium healthcare, or support a family. Fat FIRE eliminates the need to downsize your life — you retire when your portfolio is large enough to sustain your spending indefinitely.
          </p>

          <p class="mb-4">
            Many people start with Lean FIRE as their initial target and adjust upward as their income grows. The beauty of this fat fire calculator is that you can run multiple scenarios — see what your timeline looks like at 20x, 25x, and 30x — and choose the strategy that fits your goals.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="border-t border-hairline bg-canvas py-16">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 sm:px-6">
        <h2 class="mb-8 text-center text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-ink" style="letter-spacing: -0.02em;">
          Frequently Asked Questions
        </h2>

        <div class="space-y-4">
          <details class="group rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4 shadow-sm">
            <summary class="cursor-pointer py-2 text-sm font-medium text-ink">What is the difference between Lean FIRE and Fat FIRE?</summary>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-body">Lean FIRE requires <strong>20x your annual expenses</strong> saved (using a 5% withdrawal rate), while Fat FIRE requires <strong>30x your annual expenses</strong> (using a 3.33% withdrawal rate). On $50,000 of annual spending, that is a $500,000 difference: $1,000,000 for Lean FIRE vs $1,500,000 for Fat FIRE. Lean FIRE means retiring sooner on a tighter budget; Fat FIRE means working longer for more comfort and a larger safety margin.</p>
          </details>

          <details class="group rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4 shadow-sm">
            <summary class="cursor-pointer py-2 text-sm font-medium text-ink">Which is better, Lean FIRE or Fat FIRE?</summary>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-body">Neither is inherently better — it depends on your values and goals. Lean FIRE is better if you prioritize retiring quickly and are comfortable living on less. Fat FIRE is better if you want to maintain your current lifestyle, need to cover healthcare or family expenses, and prefer a larger financial cushion. Use our fat fire calculator to test both scenarios and see which timeline works for you.</p>
          </details>

          <details class="group rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4 shadow-sm">
            <summary class="cursor-pointer py-2 text-sm font-medium text-ink">Can I start with Lean FIRE and switch to Fat FIRE later?</summary>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-body">Absolutely. Many people start with Lean FIRE as their initial target because it is faster to reach, then adjust upward as their income grows or lifestyle preferences change. Running scenarios at 20x, 25x, and 30x in our calculator helps you see exactly how each target affects your retirement timeline.</p>
          </details>

          <details class="group rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4 shadow-sm">
            <summary class="cursor-pointer py-2 text-sm font-medium text-ink">What is a Fat FIRE number?</summary>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-body">Your Fat FIRE number is the total portfolio value you need to retire while maintaining your current lifestyle. It is calculated by multiplying your annual expenses by 30. For example, if you spend $80,000 per year, your Fat FIRE number is $2,400,000. This larger portfolio provides a 3.33% withdrawal rate — more conservative than the standard 25x rule — giving you a bigger safety margin against inflation and market volatility.</p>
          </details>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="border-t border-hairline bg-canvas py-16">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 text-center sm:px-6">
        <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-ink" style="letter-spacing: -0.02em;">
          Explore Other FIRE Strategies
        </h2>
        <p class="mb-8 text-body">Compare different approaches to find the right one for your lifestyle.</p>

        <div class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
          <a href="/lean-fire-calculator" class="group rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-5 text-left shadow-sm transition-all hover:shadow-md">
            <h3 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink group-hover:text-link">Lean FIRE Calculator</h3>
            <p class="text-xs text-body">Minimalist approach with lower expenses.</p>
          </a>
          <a href="/coast-fire-calculator" class="group rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-5 text-left shadow-sm transition-all hover:shadow-md">
            <h3 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink group-hover:text-link">Coast FIRE Calculator</h3>
            <p class="text-xs text-body">Let compound interest do the heavy lifting.</p>
          </a>
          <a href="/barista-fire-calculator" class="group rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-5 text-left shadow-sm transition-all hover:shadow-md">
            <h3 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink group-hover:text-link">Barista FIRE Calculator</h3>
            <p class="text-xs text-body">Work part-time, let investments cover the rest.</p>
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
</PageLayout>
